So I already told you that autophagy mobilizes nutrients of

246
00:14:40.736 --> 00:14:41.516
different kinds

247
00:14:42.356 --> 00:14:44.996
to the circulation in this cachectic model.

248
00:14:45.596 --> 00:14:49.476
So we asked the question, are any of these nutrients necessary

249
00:14:49.576 --> 00:14:50.456
for tumor growth

250
00:14:51.976 --> 00:14:53.856
reciprocally to organ wasting?

251
00:14:54.956 --> 00:14:58.856
And we cannot stop nutrient mobilization specifically, but we can stop the uptake

252
00:14:58.916 --> 00:15:02.636
of these nutrients into tumors. You may know that all these nutrients are

253
00:15:02.676 --> 00:15:04.496
polar, so you need polar

254
00:15:05.896 --> 00:15:09.356
transporters that transport these polar molecules across the membrane.

255
00:15:09.726 --> 00:15:13.496
These are called SLC molecules. So we took out each of these SLC

256
00:15:13.536 --> 00:15:17.416
molecules at the plasma membrane in these tumor models and asked the question,

257
00:15:17.456 --> 00:15:20.636
which of these SLC molecules are required for

258
00:15:21.516 --> 00:15:25.356
malignant tumor growth, but not benign Rasv12 growth or

259
00:15:25.436 --> 00:15:27.516
normal development of these epithelia?

260
00:15:28.096 --> 00:15:32.056
So we identified one that behaved exactly like this, which is called

261
00:15:32.116 --> 00:15:35.636
subermesa in Drosophila, and you see that this

262
00:15:35.776 --> 00:15:39.336
reduces tumor growth, as does these other amino

263
00:15:39.356 --> 00:15:43.336
acid transporters. But only subermesa behave in a way

264
00:15:43.376 --> 00:15:47.316
that it reduces malignant tumor growth, does not affect a

265
00:15:47.336 --> 00:15:51.236
benign Rasv12 growth, or does not affect normal development of

266
00:15:51.296 --> 00:15:54.596
cells that have subermesa knocked out. So what is subermesa?

267
00:15:56.676 --> 00:16:00.136
Subermesa is most similar to the two nutrient

268
00:16:00.196 --> 00:16:03.856
transporters, SLC7A11 and SLC7A9 in

269
00:16:03.876 --> 00:16:04.276
mammals.

270
00:16:05.656 --> 00:16:09.636
SLC7A11 is kind of like a superstar in the

271
00:16:10.376 --> 00:16:13.896
cancer field. You may know that SLC7A11

272
00:16:14.236 --> 00:16:18.216
imports cysteine, so the oxidized form of cysteine into

273
00:16:18.256 --> 00:16:18.696
the cell.

274
00:16:19.516 --> 00:16:23.296
Cysteine is reduced to form cysteine that can be

275
00:16:23.356 --> 00:16:27.236
combined with other building blocks to make glutathione

276
00:16:27.276 --> 00:16:30.076
within the cell to provide reductive power.

277
00:16:31.296 --> 00:16:34.576
And the enzyme GPX4 is used in glutathione to

278
00:16:34.656 --> 00:16:36.826
detoxify peroxinitrosated lipids that

279
00:16:36.896 --> 00:16:40.536
are produced in transformed

280
00:16:40.596 --> 00:16:41.976
cells, often by

281
00:16:44.156 --> 00:16:45.416
high metabolism.

282
00:16:46.396 --> 00:16:47.496
If this doesn't work,

283
00:16:48.536 --> 00:16:50.676
these transformed cells die from ferroptosis.

284
00:16:51.956 --> 00:16:54.116
So iron-dependent cell death. There is a

285
00:16:56.056 --> 00:16:59.836
similar nutrient transporter called SLC7A9 that is known to be

286
00:16:59.876 --> 00:17:03.456
required for cysteine re-uptake from urine in the kidney.

287
00:17:04.737 --> 00:17:08.576
And so we were interested to go further along this way since we know that these

288
00:17:08.636 --> 00:17:12.596
tumors that we study have very high ROS produced by

289
00:17:12.636 --> 00:17:13.237
mitochondria.

290
00:17:14.257 --> 00:17:17.997
And so we looked at these ferroptosis

291
00:17:18.096 --> 00:17:22.086
markers, which is 4-Hydroxynonenal, a lipid aldehyde that

292
00:17:22.096 --> 00:17:24.216
is produced by this lipid peroxidation.

293
00:17:24.856 --> 00:17:28.776
Also a direct marker, a lipid marker that fluoresces upon

294
00:17:28.786 --> 00:17:32.476
peroxidation. We see in both these situations, although

295
00:17:32.536 --> 00:17:36.056
tumors do have high ROS, they do not show signs of

296
00:17:36.116 --> 00:17:39.616
ferroptosis. They show signs of ferroptosis only when you take away

297
00:17:39.656 --> 00:17:42.796
subermesa. So that protects against ferroptosis in the fly model.

298
00:17:43.826 --> 00:17:47.336
We can rescue this by providing subermesa back into the fly.

299
00:17:47.396 --> 00:17:50.216
It both rescues ferroptotic markers and tumor growth.

300
00:17:52.476 --> 00:17:55.156
And so then next we asked the question, does this compare to

301
00:17:55.336 --> 00:17:58.196
SLC7A11 or A9 in the mammalian system?

302
00:17:58.276 --> 00:18:02.236
So first we modeled it using AlphaFold and a predicted

303
00:18:02.356 --> 00:18:05.756
structure of subermesa in the fly and compared it to either

304
00:18:05.836 --> 00:18:09.376
SLC7A11 or A9. We could see that it's more

305
00:18:09.536 --> 00:18:13.016
similar structurally when modeled to A9 than

306
00:18:13.116 --> 00:18:16.988
A11.Similarly, we could model it and see that

307
00:18:17.048 --> 00:18:19.868
it fits the human partner,

308
00:18:20.008 --> 00:18:23.828
CDA98, which is a chaperone that

309
00:18:24.148 --> 00:18:28.068
shuttles it to the plasma membrane very well.

310
00:18:28.908 --> 00:18:32.268
So then we asked the biological question, can we put these

311
00:18:32.588 --> 00:18:36.528
human potential orthologs into the fly and see whether they

312
00:18:36.588 --> 00:18:38.868
rescued the ferroptosis and tumor growth in the fly?

313
00:18:38.898 --> 00:18:42.868
And we could see that SLC7A9 readily could rescue both

314
00:18:42.908 --> 00:18:46.468
ferroptosis and tumor growth in the system, whereas A11 could

315
00:18:46.528 --> 00:18:47.288
not.

316
00:18:56.428 --> 00:18:57.848
The wrong way. Let's see.

317
00:19:01.308 --> 00:19:05.088
Sorry about that. So then next we asked the question, since

318
00:19:05.208 --> 00:19:09.068
SLC7A9 seems to be the counterpart of subermesa in the fly, we

319
00:19:09.128 --> 00:19:12.668
asked the question whether A9 has a functionality in pancreatic

320
00:19:12.728 --> 00:19:16.448
cancer in mammals. So first we looked at using

321
00:19:16.468 --> 00:19:20.428
DepMap, looked at the expression levels of SLC7A9, and found that it

322
00:19:20.488 --> 00:19:23.928
was expressed similar to A11, so it's increased in

323
00:19:23.988 --> 00:19:27.728
pancreatic cancer, as is NRF2, which is known

324
00:19:27.808 --> 00:19:30.828
to be upregulated and used by

325
00:19:30.848 --> 00:19:34.128
pancreatic cancer cells to fight off ROS,

326
00:19:34.828 --> 00:19:38.468
as are enzymes used to make glutathione, and the

327
00:19:38.868 --> 00:19:42.588
enzyme that uses glutathione to detoxify lipid peroxidation.

328
00:19:43.508 --> 00:19:47.328
So then we asked the question, if you take out A11

329
00:19:47.348 --> 00:19:50.808
and A9 in pancreatic cancer, how do they compare in

330
00:19:50.848 --> 00:19:54.728
functionality in that system? So what you can see here

331
00:19:54.788 --> 00:19:58.768
is the growth curve of a pancreatic cancer cell line, HPAF-2, but

332
00:19:58.808 --> 00:20:01.048
this is also true for other pancreatic cell lines.

333
00:20:01.828 --> 00:20:05.668
When we take out SLC7A11, we can find, like other people have

334
00:20:05.678 --> 00:20:08.048
shown before, that it reduces

335
00:20:09.068 --> 00:20:12.988
growth of these cells. If you take out SLC7A9, it

336
00:20:13.048 --> 00:20:16.248
also reduces growth of these cells, but they do not affect

337
00:20:16.928 --> 00:20:18.968
normal cells, which is HPDE

338
00:20:19.928 --> 00:20:23.848
line, which is shown here. Both are required for keeping

339
00:20:23.908 --> 00:20:27.848
glutathione levels high within the cells, and both are required to

340
00:20:27.968 --> 00:20:28.508
fight off

341
00:20:29.488 --> 00:20:31.728
ferroptosis markers in these cells.

342
00:20:32.068 --> 00:20:35.848
So SLC7A9 is working alongside

343
00:20:36.068 --> 00:20:39.648
SLC7A11 in the system to import

344
00:20:40.148 --> 00:20:43.768
cysteine, generate glutathione, and fight off ferroptosis.

345
00:20:45.488 --> 00:20:49.008
We think this is fighting off ferroptosis because we can rescue

346
00:20:49.448 --> 00:20:52.988
SLC7A9 just like SLC7A11 by

347
00:20:53.068 --> 00:20:55.908
either reducing lipid peroxidation

348
00:20:56.528 --> 00:20:59.957
by adding liproxstatin or directly adding

349
00:20:59.968 --> 00:21:03.748
glutathione to the cells. That helps them fight off lipid

350
00:21:03.768 --> 00:21:04.468
peroxidation.

351
00:21:06.288 --> 00:21:09.508
So then finally, we asked this question in

352
00:21:10.628 --> 00:21:11.548
the mouse by

353
00:21:12.948 --> 00:21:15.628
transplanting xenografts into the pancreas

354
00:21:16.788 --> 00:21:19.488
of stable knockdown cells for A9 or A11.

355
00:21:20.148 --> 00:21:23.617
We see that A11, like people have reported before, have a slight reduction of

356
00:21:23.668 --> 00:21:27.348
growth, but it comes back. A9 actually has a

357
00:21:27.408 --> 00:21:31.208
stronger effect on growth than A11 does in our hands,

358
00:21:31.568 --> 00:21:35.228
and they both have markers of ferroptosis in those

359
00:21:35.248 --> 00:21:35.648
tumors.

360
00:21:36.908 --> 00:21:40.848
So does this have anything to do with autophagy that we started

361
00:21:40.888 --> 00:21:44.278
out with? So if you look at levels of cysteine in

362
00:21:44.288 --> 00:21:48.208
circulation, so we did targeted metabolomics to look at this, we could see

363
00:21:48.268 --> 00:21:51.788
that as the tumor grows, there is an increase of cysteine in circulation

364
00:21:52.348 --> 00:21:56.258
in this model. If you take away autophagy in the whole animal, you

365
00:21:56.288 --> 00:21:56.748
see that this

366
00:21:58.528 --> 00:22:01.948
mobilization do not occur. And if you look at the ferroptotic

367
00:22:02.068 --> 00:22:05.888
markers in the different situations and permutations with tumors,

368
00:22:06.468 --> 00:22:10.328
we see that in the RasScribble tumors, we do not have

369
00:22:10.368 --> 00:22:14.188
ferroptosis. If you look at the autophagy background

370
00:22:15.408 --> 00:22:19.168
animals, where autophagy is taken out both in the tumor and in the

371
00:22:19.208 --> 00:22:22.888
host, we see the appearance of ferroptotic markers specifically

372
00:22:22.928 --> 00:22:24.888
within tumor cells and not neighboring cells.

373
00:22:25.408 --> 00:22:28.828
Whereas if you take away autophagy in the tumor itself, there is no ferroptotic

374
00:22:28.868 --> 00:22:29.308
markers.

375
00:22:30.468 --> 00:22:30.848
And so,

376
00:22:32.048 --> 00:22:35.848
then next, of course, now this question is, is

377
00:22:36.428 --> 00:22:39.928
cysteine and glutathione limiting for these tumors in the system?

378
00:22:40.668 --> 00:22:41.568
So when we look at

379
00:22:43.108 --> 00:22:46.168
the animals that are autophagy deficient, where you have

380
00:22:46.788 --> 00:22:50.548
ferroptosis going on, and we feed them orally

381
00:22:50.608 --> 00:22:54.188
N-acetylcysteine or glutathione to replenish or increase

382
00:22:54.518 --> 00:22:58.188
the circulatory availability of cysteine, we could

383
00:22:58.268 --> 00:23:01.608
reduce ferroptosis. We could also

384
00:23:01.648 --> 00:23:05.568
reduce ferroptotic markers when feeding glutathione, but not

385
00:23:05.648 --> 00:23:08.308
N-acetylcysteine when we knock down the

386
00:23:09.168 --> 00:23:12.608
subermesa or SLC7A9 in flies, probably

387
00:23:12.708 --> 00:23:16.388
suggesting that N-acetylcysteine is transported

388
00:23:16.508 --> 00:23:18.028
through subermesa in the system.

389
00:23:19.048 --> 00:23:22.808
And the million-dollar question is, of course, does this not

390
00:23:22.868 --> 00:23:26.108
only fight off ferroptosis, does it also affect tumor growth?

391
00:23:26.188 --> 00:23:29.908
And yes, it does. So the

392
00:23:29.948 --> 00:23:33.748
feeding of N-acetylcysteine and glutathione in the system

393
00:23:35.048 --> 00:23:38.648
not only fights ferroptosis, but it makes the tumor rebound.

394
00:23:39.728 --> 00:23:43.368
So I hope I convinced you that using the flies have been

395
00:23:43.708 --> 00:23:45.888
a good model in which to ask the question,

396
00:23:47.228 --> 00:23:48.888
how does the animal

397
00:23:50.768 --> 00:23:54.508
lead to organ wasting, and does organ wasting reciprocally

398
00:23:54.618 --> 00:23:58.348
affect the tumor growth? And in this case, we have identified an amino

399
00:23:58.408 --> 00:24:01.828
acid, a metabolite, that is mobilized from

400
00:24:02.028 --> 00:24:05.888
systemic tissues to help the tumor growth, not as a building block, but to

401
00:24:05.928 --> 00:24:07.048
fight off cell death.

402
00:24:07.888 --> 00:24:09.748
Thank you. I'll stop here and take any questions.

403
00:24:22.256 --> 00:24:23.436
Beautiful talk, Tore.

